1959 JAGUAR MK IX

This 1959 Mark 9 was donated to the Eastern Shore Public Library to help raise money for a badly needed new main library in this rural area in coastal Virginia. The owner of the car purchased it in an estate auction in 2004, spent approximately $6,000 upgrading the brakes and fuel system, and after driving the car for about six months put it away in a barn on his farm. The car remained in the barn for the next 14 years, and the owner took it out last fall to donate to the Eastern Shore Public Library Foundation, a non-profit charged with raising funds to construct a new library and heritage center in the town of Parksley, on Virginia's Eastern Shore.

This Jaguar is remarkably original and intact and is an excellent candidate for restoration. The woodwork is in its original finish, and the upholstery is in good shape. The only areas that show much wear are the driver's seat and the carpet. The tool kits in both front doors have all the original wrenches, pliers, and pumps for bleeding the brakes. The odometer shows 23,782 miles. The car has some surface rust on the trunk lid, but appears to have the original paint. As the photographs show, there is a small amount of rust at the bottom of the rocker panels and along the lip beneath the rear bumper. But for a car nearly 60 years old, the car is in remarkable original condition.
The Jaguar is offered for sale at $35,000. It is being kept at a private residence and will be shown to prospective buyers by appointment.

1969 Jaguar E-Type Series II 2+2 4.2 Litre 6-Cylinder.  Owned by a discerning collector, this E Type is a show quality car. Having just over 60,000 miles traveled since new, a car of this originality is rare today in the E-Type market.  This is a car that is ready to show or use for road touring. It is a fantastic car both in drivablilty and looks.

The car is finished in the original color combination of Carmen Red with Black Connolly Leather.  The interior is original with the exception of the two front seats. They have been rebuilt with fresh foams and hides from the UK. The smell of the Connolly Hides are still present. The car has just received a Concours quality bare metal respray by one of the leading auto restoration firms in South Florida. From the factory this E Type car is equipped with the options of Air Conditioning and the 3-Speed Automatic Transmission.

While in the current ownership of the last several years, the Jaguar has undergone a full and comprehensive servicing with a British Car Specialist. The services having been preformed include replacing all fluids and filters. The braking system was thoroughly gone through, replacing all four calipers, as well as the rotors and pads. A new pair of auxiliary radiator fans along with a fresh water pump have been fitted. All of the body and window seal rubber were replaced, as the original had begun to deteriorate from age. Also, a new correct OEM, not an aftermarket, windscreen glass was sourced and installed with the fresh seal, due to the original beginning to delaminate. A complete, manifold back Bell Exhaust Stainless Steel system was also sourced and fitted to the car. The exhaust note is fantastic. There has been a new correct steering wheel fitted, but the original will be supplied with the car.

The drivability and handling of the car was improved with a fresh set of Vredestein tires with new inner tubes. The trailing arm bushings have be replaced, along with stub axle seals and the wheel seals. The overall drive quality of the car is tight and responsive, with no play or wandering.

The body is straight and shows no previous evidence of bodywork from corrosion or accident damage. The undercarriage is clean, as is the engine compartment. The chrome trim is bright and free of any major flaws. The rear cargo area and spare tire well are like new. The spare wire wheel spare, the factory jack, lead wheel hammer, and center knock off tool, as well as the original owner's manual are with the car.
